(1987-Flight Delay Analysis)¶

by (Mohamed Hamdy)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes arrival and departure information about some commercial flights within USA, Data includes around 29 feature in each year from 1987 to 2008. However, we wil start only with 1987 dataset.

In [11]:
# Converting month column to string 
df["Month"] = df["Month"].apply(str)
# Replace 10,11,12 month by the month name instead 
df["Month"] = df["Month"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('10', "Oct"))
df["Month"] = df["Month"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('11', "Nov"))
df["Month"] = df["Month"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('12', "Dec"))
In [12]:
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(str)
# Replace week numbers to week names instead
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('1', "Mon"))
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('2', "Tue"))
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('3', "Wed"))
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('4', "Thur"))
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('5', "Fri"))
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('6', "Sat"))
df["DayOfWeek"] = df["DayOfWeek"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('7', "Sun"))

# Relation between Distnace and Arrival delay

base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.regplot(data=df2,x='Distance',y='ArrDelay',color=base_color,fit_reg=False,x_jitter=.8,scatter_kws={'alpha':0.2});
plt.xlim((0,6000));
plt.title('Relation between Distance and Arrival Delay ',fontsize=20, fontweight=0, color='purple', style='italic');
Obviously we can see that in short distance range, flights are more prone to arrive early. However, in long distances (more than 2000 Mile) The early arrivals started to decline and eventually disappeared after 3000 mile, Also we can find that most of the delayed ttime falls between 0 and 500 min¶

# Engineering new feature from departure delay to categorical feature delayed or not 
def delay_dep(df2):
# Negative values means arrived early so not late  (NO)
    if df2['DepDelay'] <0:
        return "No"
# Positive values means arrived late so will be (Yes)
    if df2['DepDelay'] > 0:
        return "Yes"

Conclusion¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

From Bivariate & Multivariate plots, we found out that October has the most flight frequency, followed by December, and November.Moreover, Thursday, Wednesday, and Tuesday are the most months with the highest frequency flights.

Cancelled schedualed flights in (1987) were most occured in December at (Monday, Tuesday, and Sundays)

Since we have engineered two extra features the categorical departure and arrival delay, we will finalize our findings¶

The average amount of departure delay most happened in December, specially in Wednesday, Tuesday, Sundays, Thursdays on the other hand Thursday, Wednesday, and Tuesdays have the most delayed flights number In conclusion we can say that Wednsday and Tuesday are the most common day of weeks with high average of delay time and high number of delayed flights

According to arrival delays¶

The average amount of arrival delay most happened in December, specially in Wednesday, Tuesday, Thursdays, Sundays on the other hand Thursday, Wednesday, and Tuesdays have the most delayed flights number which is the same of departure days In conclusion we can say that Wednsday and Tuesday are the most common day of weeks with high average of delay time and higher number of delayed flights.

Distance with delays in specific days¶

The long distance flights most occured in Saturdays and Sundays in all months we confirmed by two plots that the longer the flight distance the higher the possibility of the flight being delayed in departure However, we discovered that in short distance flights, the flights are more prone to arrive late.

Unique carriers with departure and arrival delays¶

The most common used carriers are (DL, AA, UA and CO) The most carriers with the highes average of arrival delays are (PS, AS, and DL), although PS ad AS have very low frequency usage comparing to other types. The most carriers with the highes average of departure delays are (PS, CO, and AS), although PS ad AS have very low frequency usage comparing to other types. Also we discovered that carriers that used in long distance flights are (UA, CO, and AA)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Interestingly, CO carriertype comes after PS in departure delay average time with the following order (PS, CO, and AS) Despite Some carrier types departure delay avergae time was relatively high but slightly low and not relative in arrival delay avergae time For instance, PS is almost the avg delay time in departure and arrival.However, in CO, AS, EA was higher average delay time in departure than in arrival, DL type has an average departure delay of 7 minutes but the arrival was 12 minutes delay.

Distance¶

The longer the distance the more pribability of fligh being late The long distance most occured in Saturdays

Finalizing¶

When unique carrier types are PS, AS, or CO we can predict high probability of delay in departure and arrival December is a rush month with a high flight frequency so we can expect delay and flight cancellation Wednsaday, Thursday, and Tuesday are rush days with high probability of delays amount and the event itself
